<handout xml:id="handout-section-5-3-diagonalization">
  <title>5.3 Diagonalization</title>

  <page xml:id="p-5-3-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <p>
      <em>Motivation:</em> It can be useful to take large powers of matrices, for example <m>A^k</m> for large <m>k</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>But:</em> Multiplying two <m>n\times n</m> matrices requires roughly <m>n^3</m> computations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Question:</em> Is there a more efficient way to compute <m>A^k</m>?
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-5-3-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Similar matrices</li>
        <li>Diagonal, similar, and diagonalizable matrices</li>
        <li>Diagonalizing matrices</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Determine whether a matrix can be diagonalized, and if possible diagonalize a square matrix.</li>
        <li>Apply diagonalization to compute matrix powers.</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p><nbsp/></p>


    <definition xml:id="def-similar-matrices">
      <title>Similarity</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Two <m>n\times n</m> matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <term>similar</term> if there exists an invertible matrix <m>P</m> such that <m>A=PBP^{-1}.</m></p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Matrix similarity is an <em>equivalence relation</em> meaning:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p workspace="true">
            <em>Reflexive Property</em>: Every matrix <m>A</m> is similar to itself.
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Proof: Let <m>A</m> be any <m>n\times n</m> matrix and let <m>P = I_n</m>. Then <me>A = I_nAI_n = I_nAI_n^{-1} = PAP^{-1}</me>. Thus, <m>A</m> is similar to <m>A</m>.
            </p>
            </solution> 
        </li>
        <li>
          <p workspace="true">
            <em>Symmetric Property</em>: If <m>A</m> is similar to <m>B</m>, then <m>B</m> is similar to <m>A</m>.
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Proof: Suppose <m>A = PBP^{-1}</m> for some invertible matrix <m>P</m>. By multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>P^{-1}</m> on the left and <m>P</m> on the right we get <m>P^{-1}AP = P^{-1}(PBP^{-1})P = B</m>. Letting <m>R = P^{-1}</m>, we have that <m>B = RAR^{-1}</m>, so <m>B</m> is similar to <m>A</m>. 
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p workspace="true">
            <em>Transitive Property</em>: If <m>A</m> is similar to <m>B</m> and <m>B</m> is similar to <m>C</m>, then <m>A</m> is similar to <m>C</m>.
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Proof: Suppose <m>A = PBP^{-1}</m> and <m>B = RCR^{-1}</m>. Then we have that <me>A = PBP^{-1} = P(RCR^{-1})P^{-1} = (PR)C(PR)^{-1}</me>, so <m>A</m> is similar to <m>C</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>

  <page>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-similar-same-charpoly" workspace="true">
      <title>Characteristic Polynomial of Similar Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are similar, then they have the same characteristic polynomial.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Recall that <m>\det(A - \lambda I)</m> and <m>\det(B - \lambda I)</m> are the characteristic polynomials of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, respectively. Since <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are similar, we have that <m>A = PBP^{-1}</m> for some invertible matrix <m>P</m>. Note the following:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\begin{eqnarray*} \det(A - \lambda I) \amp = \amp \det (PBP^{-1} - \lambda I) \\ \amp = \amp \det(PBP^{-1}  - \lambda PP^{-1}) \\ \amp = \amp \det(PBP^{-1} - P \lambda I P^{-1}) \\ \amp = \amp \det(P(B - \lambda I)P^{-1}) \\ \amp = \amp \det(P)\det(B - \lambda I)\det(P^{-1}) \\ \amp = \amp \det(P)\det(P^{-1})\det(B - \lambda I) \\ \amp = \amp \det(PP^{-1})\det(B - \lambda I) \\ \amp = \amp \det(I)\det(B - \lambda I) \\ \amp = \amp \det(B - \lambda I)\end{eqnarray*}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Thus, <m>\det(A - \lambda I) = \det(B - \lambda I)</m>, so <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> have the same characteristic polynomial.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      Notes: 
      <ul>
        <li>Similar matrices have exactly the same eigenvalues with exactly the same algebraic multiplicity for each eigenvalue and exactly the same geometric multiplicity for each eigenvalue.</li>
        <li>The converse of <xref ref="thm-similar-same-charpoly"/> is not true; that is, just because two matrices have the same characterisitc polynomial, that does not mean that they are similar. For example,
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          \quad\text{and}\quad
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        have the same characteristic polynomial, but are not similar because the eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 0</m> does not have the same geometric multiplicty for each matrix.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          True or false: If <m>A </m> is similar to the identity matrix, then <m>A</m> is equal to the identity matrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            If <m>A </m> is similar to <m>I</m>, then there exists an invertible matrix <m>P</m> so that <m>A = PIP^{-1} = PP^{-1} = I</m>. Thus, <m>A</m> must be the identity matrix.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-3-diagonal-matrices">
    <title>Diagonal Matrices</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-diagonal-matrix">
      <title>Diagonal Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A matrix is <term>diagonal</term> if the only nonzero entries (if any) lie on the main diagonal.
          In this course, we work only with square diagonal matrices.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>Examples of diagonal matrices:</p>
    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 2\end{bmatrix},\quad
      \begin{bmatrix}2\end{bmatrix},\quad
      I_n,\quad
      \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p><nbsp/></p>



    <p>
      If <m>A</m> is diagonal, then <m>A^k</m> is easy to compute by raising diagonal entries to the <m>k</m>-th power.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-3-powers-diagonal">
      <title>Example: Powers of a Diagonal Matrix</title>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
                <p>Let <me> A=\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 0.5 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Compute <m>A^2</m> and <m>A^k</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <me>A^2 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0.5 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0.5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3^2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0.5^2 \end{bmatrix}</me>. It follows that <me>A^k = \begin{bmatrix} 3^k \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0.5^k \end{bmatrix}.</me>
            </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1.5in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Is this as easy to do if <m>A</m> is <em>not</em> diagonal?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Then <me>A^2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 10 \\ 15 \amp 22 \end{bmatrix}</me>. There is no apparant pattern like there is when <m>A</m> is diagonal.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1.5in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What about if <m>A</m> is <em>similar</em> to a diagonal matrix?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Suppose <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m> for some invertible matrix <m>P</m> and some diagonal matrix <m>D</m>. Note that <me>A^2 = (PDP^{-1})^2 = (PDP^{-1})(PDP^{-1}) = PDIDP^{-1} = PD^2P^{-1}</me>. It follows that <m>A^k = PD^kP^{-1}</m>. Therefore, if we know that <m>A</m> is similar to a diagonal matrix, then we can calculate power of <m>A</m> much faster than expected.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-3-diagonalization-definition">
    <title>Diagonalization</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-diagonalizable">
      <title>Diagonalizable Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A matrix <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}</m> is <term>diagonalizable</term> if it is similar to a diagonal matrix
          <m>D</m>; that is, there exists an invertible matrix <m>P</m> such that
        </p>
        <me>
          A=PDP^{-1}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <solution>
        <p>
            First, let's identify <m>D</m>. Since <m>D</m> is diagonal, every entry not on the diagonal must be zero. Therefore, to identify <m>D</m>, we need to identify the <m>n</m> entries on the diagonal. By <xref ref="thm-similar-same-charpoly"/>, <m>A</m> and <m>D</m> must have the same characteristic polynomial. Thus, they must have the same eigenvalues. Since <m>D</m> is diagonal, it is both upper and lower triangular. Therefore, by <xref ref="thm-triangular-diagonal-are-eigs"/>, the eigenvalues of <m>D</m> are the entries on the diagonal. Hence, the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> must be the diagonal entries of <m>D</m>. So, if the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>\lambda_1, \lambda_2, \dots, \lambda_n</m> (listing repeated eigenvalues the appropriate number of times), then <me> D = \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 \amp  \amp  \amp \\ \amp \lambda_2 \amp  \amp \\ \amp  \amp \ddots \amp \\ \amp  \amp  \amp \lambda_n \end{bmatrix} </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Caution 1</em>: The above reasoning assumes that the <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m> has <m>n</m> real eigenvalues (counting multiplicity). What if <m>A</m> has fewer than <m>n</m> eigenvalues. For example, if <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, then <m>A</m> has ZERO real eigenvalues (check this). If <m>A</m> has fewer than <m>n</m> eigenvalues, then we WILL NOT be able to fill all the missing entries of <m>D</m>. We couldn't just fill the gaps with 0's because that would imply that <m>D</m> had more 0 eigenvalues than <m>A</m>. Therefore, in the case where <m>A</m> has fewer than <m>n</m> eigenvalues; that is, when the algebraic multiplicities of the eigenvalues add up to less than <m>n</m>, then it is IMPOSSIBLE to form <m>D</m>. Thus, <m>A</m> would NOT be diagonalizable.  
        </p>
        <p><nbsp/></p>
        <p>
            Assuming we can find <m>D</m>, we now need to find <m>P</m>. Let <m>P = \begin{bmatrix} \vec v_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec v_n \end{bmatrix}</m>. Then, we can rearrange the equation <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m> my multiplying by <m>P</m> on the right of both sides to get <m>AP = PD</m>. Note that <me>AP = A\begin{bmatrix} \vec v_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec v_n\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} A\vec v_1 \amp \cdots \amp A\vec v_n \end{bmatrix}</me> and <me>PD = \begin{bmatrix}\vec v_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec v_n \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 \amp  \amp  \amp \\ \amp \lambda_2 \amp  \amp \\ \amp  \amp \ddots \amp \\ \amp  \amp  \amp \lambda_n \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1\vec v_1 \amp \cdots \amp \lambda_n\vec v_n \end{bmatrix}</me>. Since <m>AP = PD</m>, we can set corresponding columns equal to each other to find <m>A\vec v_i = \lambda_i\vec v_i</m>. Since <m>\vec v_i \neq \vec 0</m> (else <m>P</m> would not be invertible) we have that the columns <m>\vec v_i</m> must be eigenvectors of <m>A</m> corresponding to <m>\lambda_i</m>!
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Caution 2</em>: Note that <m>P</m> would fail to be invertible if the columns were linearly independent. Therefore, we must have that the vectors <m>\vec v_i</m> are linearly independent. Are we guaranteed to be able to find <m>n</m> linearly independent eigenvectors? This is only possible if every eigenspace is as big as it is supposed to be. For example, if the eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 2</m> has algebraic multiplicity 3, then we expect the <m>2</m>-eigenspace to be 3-dimensional. If it is not, then it is impossible for us to find 3 linearly independent eigenvectors corresponding to <m>\lambda = 2</m>. Therefore, it would be impossible to form <m>P</m> since <m>P</m> must contain <m>3</m> linearly independent vectors to match with the <m>3</m> <m>\lambda = 2</m>'s which are on the diagonal of <m>D</m>. Recall that the dimension of the eigenspace is the geometric multiplicity. Therefore, we are unable to find an invertible <m>P</m> when any eigenvalue has geometric multiplicity less than its algebraic multiplicity. If that happens for any of the eigenvalues, then <m>A</m> is NOT diagonalizable.
        </p>
    </solution>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-3-diagonalization-theorem">
    <title>Characterizing Diagonalizability</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-diagonalizable-iff-n-lin-ind-eigenvectors" workspace="true">
      <title>Diagonalization Criterion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A matrix <m>A</m> is diagonalizable if and only if <m>A</m> has <m>n</m> linearly independent eigenvectors.
          Equivalently,
        </p>
        <me>
          A = \bigl[\vec v_1\ \vec v_2\ \cdots\ \vec v_n\bigr]\,
          \begin{bmatrix}
            \lambda_1 \amp  \amp  \amp \\
             \amp \lambda_2 \amp  \amp \\
             \amp  \amp \ddots \amp \\
             \amp  \amp  \amp \lambda_n
          \end{bmatrix}
          \bigl[\vec v_1\ \vec v_2\ \cdots\ \vec v_n\bigr]^{-1},
        </me>
        <p>
          where <m>\vec v_1,\dots,\vec v_n</m> are linearly independent eigenvectors and
          <m>\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_n</m> are the corresponding eigenvalues (in order).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-diagonalizable-multiplicity-conditions" workspace="true">
      <title>Algebraic vs. Geometric Multiplicity</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>A</m> is <m>n\times n</m>,</li>
          <li><m>A</m> has distinct eigenvalues <m>\lambda_1,\ldots,\lambda_k</m> with <m>k\le n</m>,</li>
          <li><m>a_i</m> is the algebraic multiplicity of <m>\lambda_i</m>,</li>
          <li><m>d_i</m> is the geometric multiplicity (dimension of the <m>\lambda_i</m>-eigenspace).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Then:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><m>d_i \le a_i</m> for all <m>i</m>.</li>
          <li>
            <m>A</m> is diagonalizable <m> \ \iff \ \sum_i d_i = n \ \iff \ d_i=a_i</m> for all <m>i</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>A</m> is diagonalizable <m>\iff</m> the eigenvectors for all eigenvalues together form a basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-n-distinct-eigs-implies-diagonalizable" workspace="true">
      <title>Diagonalization with Distinct Eigenvalues</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> is <m>n\times n</m> and has <m>n</m> distinct eigenvalues, then <m>A</m> is diagonalizable.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>

  <page>


        <example xml:id="ex-5-3-diagonalize-1" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Diagonalize if possible:</p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 3
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
    
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-3-example-2">
    <title>Example 2: Diagonalize if Possible</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-3-diagonalize-2" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Diagonalize if possible:</p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 6\\
            0 \amp -1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>



  <page xml:id="p-5-3-example-3">
    <title>Example 3: Build P and D</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-3-construct-PD" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>\lambda=3,1</m>. If possible, construct <m>P</m> and <m>D</m> such that
          <m>A=PDP^{-1}</m>. Verify by checking that <m>AP = PD</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}
            7 \amp 4 \amp 16\\
            2 \amp 5 \amp 8\\
            -2 \amp -2 \amp -5
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>

   <page xml:id="p-5-3-example-4">
    <title>Example 3: Build P and D</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-3-diagonalize-3-by-3" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Diagonalize the following matrix, if possible.
        </p>
        <me>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 4 \amp 3\\
            -4 \amp -6 \amp -3\\
            3 \amp 3 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
    
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-3-fibonacci-example">
    <title>Additional Example (if time permits)</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-3-fibonacci" workspace="true">
      <title>Diagonalization and a Famous Sequence</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Note that
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec x_k=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}\vec x_{k-1},\quad
          \vec x_0=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1\\
            1
          \end{bmatrix},\quad
          k=1,2,3,\ldots
        </me>
        <p>
          generates a well-known sequence of numbers. Use diagonalization to find a matrix expression that gives the
          <m>n</m>-th number in this sequence.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>

</handout>